
[1]client

   CLIENT, n.

   1. Among the Romans, a citizen who put himself under the protection of
   a man of distinction and influence, who, in respect to that relation,
   was called his patron. Hence in modern usage,

   2. One who applies to a lawyer or counselor for advice and direction in
   a question of law, or commits his cause to his management in
   prosecuting a claim, or defending against a suit, in a court of
   justice.

   3. A dependent.
